            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nIn the first two chapters of this section, we studied counting, number organization, and the initial concept of limits. Afterward, we explored the principle of comparisons. In this chapter, we begin studying how to navigate the number system. Therefore, we recommend studying the previous two chapters before proceeding with this one",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we are born, we cannot walk and must be carried in our parents' arms. Over time, we begin to crawl, take our first steps, and eventually learn to run. The process of learning follows a similar progression: we start with the basics and, gradually, move on to more complex concepts. In this text, we will explore the first steps of this journey in *pre-mathematics*, focusing on addition",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d6a6b284-a060-4a85-bc6c-9d2fe442254c",
                     "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A.",
                     "page": "00:08:20",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_road",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Roads\n\nFigure 1 depicts a section of the archaeological site of Teotihuacan in Mexico:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"ChronologyTeotihuacan\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('ChronologyTeotihuacan', '0%')\" src=\"images/Teotihuacan/TeotihuacanGeneral.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: General view of Teotihuacan. Photograph taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "General view of Teotihuacan city. In this photo it is possible to observe different constructions in format Talud-Tablero, and in the background we have pyramidal structures representing sacred moutains.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) not only built roads within their cities but also developed extensive networks connecting different regions. For example, the Mayas constructed **sacbes** (plural: **sacbeob**), which were white roads designed to simplify movement between cities",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "19ea1063-0ddd-4468-ad3e-2635675ca68d",
                     "text": "LaRocque, A., Leblon, B., Ek, J., and Folan, W. J.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In the southern part of the continent, the Incas created an impressive network of routes spanning 39,000 kilometers, known as the **Qhapaq Ñan**, which linked diverse regions. Portions of these routes were originally built by earlier civilizations, such as the Wari",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0bc6455e-7fdb-49cd-bf29-c3675aca4d4f",
                     "text": "Jurado, L. R. C. V.",
                     "page": "pp. 1270 - 1271",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: On Roads</b><br /><br />Roads are not exclusive to the indigenous peoples of the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>). Even today, we continue to build streets, highways, and routes that serve similar purposes—facilitating movement and connection between cities.<br /><br />Additionally, rivers, which follow natural courses, have been and continue to be used as pathways by various cultures around the world.<br /><br />Artificial roads, constructed using natural materials, are a product of human engineering. Meanwhile, nature itself creates its own pathways, such as rivers and watercourses, both of which can be described using the language of nature—mathematics.<br /><br />Based on what we have studied so far, can we identify any connections between numbers and roads?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In mathematics, roads can be represented as **axes**. Along these axes, numbers indicate measures or positions, much like the steps we take when traveling a road",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3918f1d9-8d7f-439f-8f76-e5c4ef741b5e",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"chart\"><div class=\"tick\"><span>0</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>1</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>2</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>3</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>4</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>5</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>6</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>7</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>8</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>9</span></div><div class=\"tick arrow rightarrow\"></div></div></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"desc\">Graph 1: Representation of an axis with numbers. The numbers are placed below the line, and an arrow on the right end indicates the direction in which the values increase. The source code used to generate the CSS-based image is available on <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('c7edc93c-0a41-4753-8f89-9e52904ff003'); return false;\">W3 Schools</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_sum_body",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Rereading the Order of Numbers\n\nBefore understanding the logic behind addition, it is important to review a table presented in the text *Drawing to Count*. This table uses the method *\"Yupana Inka Tawa Pukllay,\"* (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>) developed and published by Dhavit Prem from the *Yupanki Association*. The method is based on the *Yupana* described by Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala (<htcite3>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "pp. 354 - 363",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2d2ea4a5-506b-4dbf-aaa4-3a10a8fbbd9c",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9618a83e-f232-49db-84f6-fc3455a3f1d1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1",
                     "text": "Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman",
                     "page": "pp. 361 - 362",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1615",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Yupana</i></th><th>Left Hand</th><th>Right Hand</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_center\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_bottom\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"><span class=\"dot three_dot_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_up\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_center\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"><span class=\"dot two_dot_bottom\"></span> <span class=\"dot two_dot_up\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"dot dot_center\"></span></td><td id=\"tc5f1\"><img id=\"leftHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Left_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"><img id=\"rightHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Right_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\"style=\"font-size:4em;color:#00f;\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></td></tr></table><p class=\"desc\">Table 1: Representation of a  <i>Yupana</i> according to Poma de Ayala (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8'); return false;\">Prem, Dhavit, <htdate0>, pp. 355</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1'); return false;\">Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman, <htdate1>, pp. 361 - 362</a>). CSS inspirado no código de <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('48dd9187-7ecc-4f54-a387-d9ecc2497de3'); return false;\">W3School</span></a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2018",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1615",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Using the right arrows, we observe that the fingers are raised one by one, representing the numbers from 0 to 9 sequentially. Additionally, circles are added to the Yupana to illustrate the same numbers",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1",
                     "text": "Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman",
                     "page": "pp. 361 - 362",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1615",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "pp. 354 - 363",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2d2ea4a5-506b-4dbf-aaa4-3a10a8fbbd9c",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "This upward movement of the fingers, used for counting, can be understood as more than just ordering. Each time we raise a finger, we can say we are transitioning between numbers by adding one. The process of addition can be visualized with the \"+\" symbol, as shown below:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>0</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>2</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>2</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>3</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>3</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>4</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>4</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>5</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>6</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>6</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>7</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>7</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>8</mn> </math></p><p><math display=\"block\"> <mn>8</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>9</mn> </math></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 1: Counting by Adding 1.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_rules",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### An Axiom of Addition\n\nWhen studying numerical families, we learn that in the decimal system, counting progresses until reaching the number nine (9), the highest position. At this point, we return to the smallest value, zero (0), and increment the digit to the left. Since addition is a way to move between numbers, this concept also applies to addition operations. We can represent this process using the vertical format for calculations",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "00f3ab60-2017-420a-99dc-56de384243e8",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "94c4d446-cc89-499b-8404-b528e5107864",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;1&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;9<br />+&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;1<br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;1 0</center></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 2: Representation of addition by adding 1 in vertical format.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "However, Calculation 2, as written, hides some important aspects of the mathematical reasoning behind it. At first glance, the number 1 above appears \"isolated\" and seems to simply \"drop\" to the result line. However, the zero (0), which represents the empty or null value (<htcite0>), is typically omitted on the left side of a number. That said, there’s nothing stopping us from making it explicit. Thus, we can rewrite Calculation 2 as follows (<htcite1>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "576e4648-77fa-4a6d-9e51-9459ced964f3",
                     "text": "Musa, Auwalu",
                     "page": "pp. 46 - 48",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "94c4d446-cc89-499b-8404-b528e5107864",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;1&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;0 9<br />+&nbsp;&nbsp;0 1<br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;1 0</center></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 3: Representation of addition in vertical format, explicitly showing the hidden zero.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In Calculation 3, we can conclude that the number 1 is not merely carried to the result line. What truly happens is that the sum of 9 + 1 equals 10. Since numbers outside the range of 0 to 9 cannot be represented as a single digit, the value exceeding the highest allowed number (nine) is carried to the line above, where it is added to the next numbers. When no number is visible on the left side, we understand that implicit zeros are present in that position",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In the explanation of Calculation 3, we used an important mathematical axiom—**the identity property of addition**—without explicitly mentioning it. But what is an axiom, and which one applies here?\n\nAn axiom is a proposition accepted as self-evident, requiring no proof. If this definition seems abstract, we can simplify it with an example of the **addition identity**",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7a9c733b-ca13-40f5-8849-19012540b028",
                     "text": "Ernst, Dana.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d26564d2-f3d4-41fa-bfd7-3e555cf6cb8f",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><i><b>Addition Identity:</b> There exists a number, zero (0), such that when added to any number <b>a</b>, the result is the number <b>a</b> itself:<br /> a + 0 = a</i></li></ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "This concept can be easily illustrated using our hands. When we keep all the fingers of our left hand down, we represent the number zero (0). By raising the fingers on our right hand, we effectively add them to the \"zero\" of the left hand, resulting only in the number of fingers raised on the right hand.\n\nThis idea can also be visualized in Table 1 above, making the concept more intuitive and accessible.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we explored the relationship between numbers and addition, emphasizing how numerical sequences are constructed. Furthermore, we introduced the concept of an axiom, specifically the **addition identity**, which states that any number added to zero results in the number itself.\n\nIn the next text, we will expand on this analogy, taking significant steps forward in our journey of understanding mathematical concepts.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Can we understand a number sequence as being formed by adding 1 to the previous number?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "The counting of numbers is done sequentially, where each number is separated from the next by 1. In this way, we can understand the sequence as a process of adding 1 to obtain the next number."
      },
      {
         "question": "Since the number zero (0) represents emptiness, can it always be hidden when it appears on the left?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "The definition of zero allows us to omit it when it appears on the left side of a number, but this cannot happen on the right side. For example, writing \"01\" is equivalent to writing \"1.\" However, the number \"10\" is completely different, as it represents a distinct value."
      }
   ],
